    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Trea Turner** (81.27) and **Kyle Schwarber** (79.42) headlining our offensive attack. Both benefit immensely from the matchup against Assad, with **Trea Turner** capitalizing on an elite 19% SP skill advantage and a prime leadoff spot that boosts his floor significantly. **Kyle Schwarber** remains a lock in the outfield, bolstered by his elite 0.402 xwOBA and favorable wind conditions that project to amplify his power output. **Caleb Durbin** (63.84) and **Josh Smith** (62.54) round out our top-tier plays, both thriving in favorable matchups against Ober and Severino, respectively. While **Caleb Durbin** faces an elite hold pitcher, his positioning in the two-hole and solid park factors keep him firmly in the \"Strong\" start category.\n\nBench decisions were dictated by efficiency, with **Carson Benge** (36.52) falling just short of the 40-point threshold required to displace our current starters. His matchup against Wrobleski presents a hurdle, as the opposing SP skill disadvantage and the L/L platoon friction outweighed his base offensive profile. Looking at our lower-scoring starters, **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (41.99) and **Logan O'Hoppe** (44.53) are operating near our performance floor. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** specifically faces a tough task against Sanchez, where his projected score is suppressed by a -19% SP skill factor and negative platoon splits, necessitating a watchful eye for early-game defensive substitutions.\n\nWe remain cautious regarding the \"Lineup Pending\" status of **Josh Smith** and **Hyeseong Kim**, as any shift out of their projected batting spots will require a re-evaluation of their daily efficiency scores. **Yordan Alvarez** (57.19) also presents a marginal risk today; although he is a core component of our roster, the high-skill matchup against Kirby slightly limits his ceiling. As we hunt for scarce stolen bases, we are relying on the speed profiles of **Trea Turner**, 